// Problem
An array ğ‘ of ğ‘š positive integers is good if for all pairs ğ‘– and ğ‘— (1â‰¤ğ‘–,ğ‘—â‰¤ğ‘š), max(ğ‘ğ‘–,ğ‘ğ‘—) is divisible by min(ğ‘ğ‘–,ğ‘ğ‘—).

You are given an array ğ‘ of ğ‘› positive integers. You can perform the following operation:

    Select an index ğ‘– (1â‰¤ğ‘–â‰¤ğ‘›) and an integer ğ‘¥ (0â‰¤ğ‘¥â‰¤ğ‘ğ‘–) and add ğ‘¥ to ğ‘ğ‘–, in other words, ğ‘ğ‘–:=ğ‘ğ‘–+ğ‘¥. After this operation, ğ‘ğ‘–â‰¤1018 should be satisfied. 

You have to construct a sequence of at most ğ‘› operations that will make ğ‘ good. It can be proven that under the constraints of the problem, such a sequence of operations always exists.

// Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer ğ‘¡ (1â‰¤ğ‘¡â‰¤10^4) â€” the number of test cases. The description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a single integer ğ‘› (1â‰¤ğ‘›â‰¤10^5) â€” the length of the array ğ‘.

The second line of each test case contains ğ‘› space-separated integers ğ‘1,ğ‘2,â€¦,ğ‘ğ‘› (1â‰¤ğ‘ğ‘–â‰¤10^9) â€” representing the array ğ‘.

It is guaranteed that the sum of ğ‘› over all test cases does not exceed 10^5.

// Output

For each test, output a single integer p(0â‰¤ğ‘â‰¤ğ‘›) â€” denoting the number of operations in your solution.

In each of the following ğ‘ lines, output two space-separated integers â€” ğ‘– and ğ‘¥.

You do not need to minimize the number of operations. It can be proven that a solution always exists.

// Example
// Input
4
4
2 3 5 5
2
4 8
5
3 4 343 5 6
3
